The ruler and each lower rank vassal (i.e. the dukes if the ruler is a king) can nominate a successor from among themselves and legitimate children and siblings of the ruler. Dukes are valid electors in both kingdoms and empires. Elective Succession is very popular with the vassals, but they will not approve if their liege personally holds too many elector titles. Women can never inherit.

The ruler and pious realm vassal (including vassals of vassals) can nominate a successor from among themselves and legitimate children and siblings of the ruler. Elective Succession is very popular with the vassals, but they will not approve if their liege personally holds too many elector titles. Value is based on the amount of people sacrificed.

The Commanders of the ghazwa can influence the selection of the new ruler. Unlike a regular elective monarchy, ghazwa electors choose a successor based on physical strength and military skill. Commanders can only elect a new ruler from among their peers. Women can never inherit.

Phonocracy is a type of government practised by faiths that put great value in human sacrifice. Inspired by the legendary reigns of terror where lives were regularly given to their gods, in a phonocracy the main merit of an individual is how much blood they have spilled in the name of a deity. Urban population is taxed more for their lives than for their money, and the rulers of phonocratic realms are elected based on their devotion rather than any sort of skill.

The Makhzen is a type of governance that has developed after the deluge in the harsh terrain of the Atlas mountains. Named after the entrepots used to stash grain tax by the sultans of old, today it refers to the unique hierarchical structure of the Maghreb. The Makhzen system, along with the usual oath of fealty, includes a type of autonomous subservience of the ferociously independent mountain tribes of the Atlas, who voluntarily serve feudal overlords, asking only to be left alone in return. Cities enjoy their own fair share of autonomy, viewing their feudal overlords as little more than protectors. Rulers under this decentralised system of governing will need to please their vassals much more than the usual feudal ruler.

The Neo-Ziamet system developed in Anatolia after the event, based on the governance of the antediluvian Ottoman Empire. A very bureaucratic way of governing, the ziamet system tends to set religion aside, gearing the state for conquest instead. Typically centralised in a single city, ziamet rulers are largely dependent on governors and bureaucrats to manage their land and collect their taxes, though the most important resource for a ziamet sultan is manpower.

The Ghazwa system resembles more of an army with a state than its vice versa. Still dependent on the oath between liege and vassal, the liege in a ghazwa is a commander elected among his peers for his leadership skills. The elected ruler has a divine obligation to spread the one true word far and wide under any means necessary. Unruly vassals are not tolerated, and places of worship are equally a source of manpower as they are faith.
